###
### Milady on-device agent SELinux allow rule.
###
### The Milady APK is platform-signed (see vendor/milady/apps/Milady/
### Android.bp), so seapp_contexts assigns its process to the
### `platform_app` SELinux domain. AOSP's stock platform_app.te does
### not include `allow platform_app app_data_file:file execute` — that
### rule lives only on `priv_app`. Without it MiladyAgentService cannot
### execve the bundled bun runtime out of /data/data/<pkg>/files/agent/
### and the on-device agent crashloops with avc:denied { execute }.
###
### A previous attempt added a custom `milady_agent` domain with a
### domain transition to scope this allow narrowly; that approach
### tripped roughly 30 AOSP neverallow checks (priv_app cannot
### auto_trans to a vendor domain, app domains cannot label files
### under /data/data, etc.). Per-domain custom labels for /data/data
### paths are supposed to be done at the seapp_contexts level, which
### would require a custom seinfo entry tied to a different signing
### certificate.
###
### For now the allow is broad: any platform_app can execve any file
### labeled app_data_file. The neverallow envelope still applies
### (no write+execute on the same file outside narrow exemptions, no
### entrypoint, etc.). This is acceptable on userdebug builds where
### the only platform_app is Milady itself; for production user
### builds the rule should be re-scoped to a custom file label set
### via restorecon from the Java service.
###
### Validated by scripts/miladyos/validate.mjs::validateSepolicy().
###
### NOTE — SELinux is NOT seccomp. If the on-device bun process exits
### with SIGSYS / code 159, that's a seccomp-bpf trap installed by the
### zygote (bionic/libc/seccomp/{arch}_app_policy.cpp) — no rule in this
### file can relax it. The seccomp mitigation is the BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_*
### env block in MiladyAgentService.startAgentProcess(); see
### sepolicy/README.md for the full diagnosis playbook.
###

allow platform_app app_data_file:file { execute execute_no_trans };
